i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBefore I switch to NixOS, I use the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Devuan Linux distro](https://www.devuan.org) (basically Debian		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwithout SystemD). Debian is infamous for the complexity of packaging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware, as you need to write a complicated Makefile just for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackaging into DEB files. In addition, complicated programs may depend		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ion lots of customized libraries. For example, my Nginx depends on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBrotli, Zlib modified by Cloudflare, BoringSSL, and a bunch of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithird-party Nginx modules. This makes it even harder to pack		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ieverything into one DEB file. Therefore, I simply gave up on DEB		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackages and started to search for better solutions.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe next solution is Docker containers. Docker containers are really		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ieasy to use,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1I started with them back in 2016	/en/article/modify-website/migrate-website-docker.lantian/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.iHowever, with continuous version updates and the addition of new		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifeatures, the memory consumption of Docker is rising as well.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`dockerd` usually takes 80-100MB RAM on my nodes, and that's not		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icounting another 20-30MB from `containerd`. For my small VPS boxes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwith only 512MB RAM, that's almost one-fourth of my total RAM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iallotment.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> RAM usage is also the main reason I switched from Debian to Devuan.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> The various processes of SystemD took some 50MB of RAM, but since		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Devuan is still using the sysvinit framework from Debian 7 and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> earlier, the resident memory usage of `init`, `udev` and `rsyslog`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> adds up to only 20MB. And as I have Docker, I don't need the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> advanced features of SystemD anyway.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> If I ever ran out of RAM on these small VPS boxes, it can get		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> anywhere from being terribly slow due to bad IO performance and slow		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> SWAP operations, to being completely frozen for high IO latency or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> being shut down for excessive IOPS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThere is a replacement for `dockerd`, of course, the Podman developed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iby Red Hat. Podman's largest difference is that it doesn't have a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresidual background process like `dockerd`, and it only creates one or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itwo processes for each running container for monitoring, logging, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDNS resolution purposes. However, lacking a background process means		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ino autostart on system bootup, and Podman relies on an external		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess manager like SystemD or Supervisord to do that. In addition,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhile Podman strives to emulate the Docker API, the compatibility work		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis still far from complete, and it is hard to use tools like Docker		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCompose with it. For me, the biggest no-go is the lack of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[IPv6 NAT](https://github.com/robbertkl/docker-ipv6nat), which		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibasically means no IPv6 connectivity in my containers, and no access		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito services in containers from the IPv6 network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis leads to the next problem: container networking is hard. By		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idefault, Docker containers get their own network namespaces with their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iown IP addresses. This means that containers cannot access each other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom `127.0.0.1 (localhost)`. Instead, they need to resolve the names		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivia DNS. For example, PHP-FPM sitting in a container cannot connect to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia MySQL database via `127.0.0.1`. It has to resolve the IP of the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontainer `mysql` with DNS before it can make a connection. Now,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprograms in containers cannot only listen on `127.0.0.1`. They need to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilisten on `0.0.0.0` instead so that the host and other containers can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaccess it. Since databases like MySQL usually default to listening on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`127.0.0.1` for security, some extra config changes are needed either		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhen packing the Docker image or using it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDNS resolution causes new issues as well. Programs may not refresh		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itheir DNS cache in time, with one major example being Nginx. For		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexample, I have two containers, A (`172.17.0.100`) and B		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i(`172.17.0.101`). I changed their config and redeployed them with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`docker-compose`. Since `docker-compose` creates the containers in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iparallel with no deterministic order, A gets `172.17.0.101` this time,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand B gets `172.17.0.100`. Since Nginx doesn't refresh DNS resolution		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresults in time, whenever I try to access A, I actually get to B, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivice versa. To avoid this issue, I have to restart all containers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irelated to A and B, and this is some extra maintenance cost.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYes, you can actually resolve this with Docker: you can set the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inetworking mode of containers to `host` (aka `--net host`) to let the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontainers share the network namespace and IPs with the host. But		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iremember that Docker containers usually listen on `0.0.0.0`? Many		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDocker images had already changed the config for you to listen on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`0.0.0.0`, and as you use `host` mode, you're exposing the port to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipublic Internet, causing a security risk. Now you need to change the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfig back to what it was. Too much trouble!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnother way that would have worked is manually assigning an IP to each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontainer, so that each of them gets the same IP after recreate. For		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iobvious reasons, manually assigning IPs to dozens of containers isn't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifun.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
