i# Installing NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe unique Nix package/config management system resolves all the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iissues above. Let's start by installing NixOS first. Since NixOS is a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idistro based on config files, the installation process comes down to 3		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isteps:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Partition the disk and mount to `/mnt`. Anyone who has installed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Arch Linux or Gentoo already knows what to do.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Generate a default config and make some changes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   `nixos-generate-config --root /mnt` will autodetect your hardware		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   and create a config at `/mnt/etc/nixos/configuration.nix`。		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Install your system based on the config file with `nixos-install`。		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe installation manual of NixOS is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[on this page](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#sec-installation),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand its ISO images can be downloaded		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[on this page](https://nixos.org/download.html).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you want to install NixOS on a VPS, but your provider cannot mount		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ian ISO for you, and your VPS is too low on RAM to boot the NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinstallation image from the network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i([Netboot.xyz](https://netboot.xyz/)), you can also use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[NixOS-Infect](https://github.com/elitak/nixos-infect) to replace your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexisting system with NixOS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> NixOS-Infect automatically mounts a Swap file on servers with low		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> RAM to avoid memory exhaustion during the installation process. But		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> if you use Btrfs, ZFS, or any filesystem that doesn't support		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> mounting a Swapfile, you need to comment out the `makeSwap` and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
