i## Managing Multiple Servers, but with NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAt the very beginning, I mentioned that one important feature of NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis managing each and every package and config with a set of Nix config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifiles. Therefore, we can use any tools we like, for example Ansible,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iRsync, or even Git, to manage the config at `/etc/nixos`. Since this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis the only config file we care about, we no longer need a bunch of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomplicated Ansible playbooks or dozens of Rsync commands. We only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ineed to overwrite `/etc/nixos`, run `nixos-rebuild switch`, and call		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit a day.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince each config update is equivalent to overwriting all programs and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfig in the whole system, you don't need to decide on which special		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iscript to use, which services to reboot, and which config files you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iforgot to copy onto the node. NixOS will automatically compare your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inew config to the last one and restart the services on demand.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS, as a Linux distro with some history, also has some software		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
