i## Binary Distribution, but with Nix Package Manager		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe Nix package manager stores binaries in paths like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/nix/store/wadmyilr414n7bimxysbny876i2vlm5r-bash-5.1-p8`. The hash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivalue at the middle corresponds to all inputs from the package config,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iincluding the version of the source code (like URLs to `tar.gz`, Git		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icommit hashes, etc.), SHA256 of the source code, compilation and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinstallation commands, and versions of all libraries it depends on. To		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imake sure the software is exactly the same, Nix compiles them in a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isandbox. Compilation scripts in the sandbox can only access the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idependent libraries. It cannot even get the system time (fixed to UNIX		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itimestamp 0 or 1970-01-01 00:00:00) or connect to the Internet.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iLet's take an example. It's well known that most programs on Linux		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idepends on the system Libc. Let's find out which Libc the bash we're		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
italking about is depending on:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i$ ldd /nix/store/wadmyilr414n7bimxysbny876i2vlm5r-bash-5.1-p8/bin/bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilinux-vdso.so.1 (0x00007ffe169d8000)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibdl.so.2 => /nix/store/mij848h2x5wiqkwhg027byvmf9x3gx7y-glibc-2.33-50/lib/libdl.so.2 (0x00007f767f863000)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibc.so.6 => /nix/store/mij848h2x5wiqkwhg027byvmf9x3gx7y-glibc-2.33-50/lib/libc.so.6 (0x00007f767f69e000)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i/nix/store/mij848h2x5wiqkwhg027byvmf9x3gx7y-glibc-2.33-50/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 => /usr/lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007f767f86a000)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis Bash can only use a Glibc in a fixed location in `/nix/store`, or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe exact copy used during compilation. Therefore, the Nix package		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanager also avoids program crashing due to shared library updates.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince programs can only use the libraries at exact paths, and an exact		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipath with config hash must correspond to the exact library, as long as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia programs works during compile time, it will continue to work exactly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithat way.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> This doesn't include cases where the program has deliberate		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> countermeasures, like generating compilation results from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> `/dev/random`, or behaving differently based on system time (aka		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> time bomb). However, these behaviors are extremely rare in normal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> programs, so for the vast majority of programs, the Nix package		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> management system can fulfill its promise.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iLikewise, If I copy this Bash and its dependent libraries to another		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
