i## Fixing System Crashes, but Luckily with NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince all binaries of NixOS are stored in `/nix/store` and there is no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iunified path, NixOS will adjust the `PATH` environment variable to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinclude all `bin` folders of packages, so you can call them directly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iin Bash; In addition, NixOS will link some config files to `/etc` so		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprograms can find them at their desired location.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf the new config files crashed the system, theoretically, you only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ineed to adjust `PATH` and links in `/etc` to recover to the last		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icorrect config, and the system will recover to an older state.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, NixOS directly provides the options in its boot menu, so		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyou can boot to a specific deployment state:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
INixOS Boot Menu	/usr/uploads/202110/nixos-bootloader.jpg	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
